[1] Region of the Americas update: PAHO
Date: Wed 26 Aug 2020
Source: Pan American Health Organization (PAHO) [abridged, edited]
https://www.paho.org/en/documents/epidemiological-update-coronavirus-disease-covid-19-26-august-2020


[Note: all maps, figures, footnotes, and references are available at the source URL above, download document]

Situation summary in the Region of the Americas
-----------------------------------------------
All 54 countries and territories in the Region of the Americas have reported COVID-19 cases and deaths. As of [22 Aug 2020], there are more than 12.3 million cases of COVID-19, including approximately 439 000 deaths, which is nearly [three times as many] reported cases and almost twice the number of reported deaths as noted on 22 Jun 2020 (4.4 million cases, including 224 000 deaths). Of the almost 8 million new cases reported in the prior 2 months, 73% were reported by [two countries]: the United States of America [accounted for ] 42% and Brazil 31%. These 2 countries also account for 54% of the new deaths reported; 29% of the new deaths were reported by Brazil and 25% by the USA, followed by 18% [by] Mexico and 9% [by] Peru.

The countries and territories with the highest cumulative incidence rates are French Guiana (2945 cases per 100 000 population) and Chile (2070/100 000), followed by Panama, Peru, the USA, Brazil, and Aruba, which each reported a cumulative incidence rate greater than 1000/100 000 (see Map 1A). The countries with the highest cumulative per capita death rate as of [22 Aug 2020] are Peru (83 deaths per 100 000 population), Chile (56/100 000), Brazil (53/100 000), and the United States of America (53/100 000) (see Map 1B).

In the Region of the Americas, while COVID-19 cases seem to have steadied in some countries and territories at the national level (such as the USA and Canada), daily notification rates are now accelerating in other countries and territories, many of which are experiencing larger outbreaks for the 1st time since the onset of the pandemic in the Region (such as countries and territories in the Caribbean subregion). A decreasing trend in the daily incidence of cases is mainly from countries in the North America subregion, primarily the United States of America (see Figure 2: Distribution of new COVID-19 cases by epidemiological week (EW) of report and by country/territory. Region of the Americas. EW 4-EW 34, 2020 [19 Jan-22 Aug 2020]). Trends throughout this report should be interpreted with caution as they are dependent on a number of factors which vary considerably between countries and territories (such as testing rates, case definitions, time delays between diagnosis, laboratory results, and official notification, etc).

- North America
The North America subregion, which consists of Canada, Mexico, and the USA, accounts for 50% of the total cases and 55% of the total deaths reported to date in the Region of the Americas. Of the approximately 3.7 million new cases, including the almost 93 000 new deaths, reported in the subregion in the [last] 2 months, [most] of the new cases were reported by the USA (89%), followed by Mexico (10%) and Canada (1%). With regard to the new deaths, approximately 58% were reported by the USA, 41% by Mexico, and 1% by Canada. All 3 countries have reported community transmission per the WHO classification for COVID-19 transmission category.

Notification of daily COVID-19 cases began increasing in epidemiological week (EW) 11 of 2020 [8-14 Mar 2020] and reached a peak in EW 30 [19-25 Jul 2020], when 516 070 new cases were reported, primarily from the USA (see Figure 3: Distribution of COVID-19 cases by epidemiological week (EW) of notification. North America subregion. EW 11-EW 34 2020 [8 Mar-22 Aug 2020]). Since then, the daily notification of cases has gradually declined, with a total of 349 737 cases reported during EW 34 [16-22 Aug 2020], a 32% decrease compared to the peak shown in Figure 3.

North America's decrease in daily case notifications is due in large part to the decreasing trend in daily cases in the USA, which had its 2nd peak at the end of July [2020]. Per the United States Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (US CDC), the percentage of respiratory specimens testing positive for SARS-CoV-2 decreased from 6.9% in EW 32 [208 Aug 2020] to 6.3% in EW 33 [9-15 Aug 2020], and decreased or remained the same in 9 of 10 Health and Human Services regions.

In Canada, average daily case counts at the national level have remained stable over the past 3 weeks, and the numbers of hospitalizations and deaths remain low overall. In Mexico, the daily notification of cases appears to be on a downward trend, with 5481 cases reported on [22 Aug 2020] (7-day moving average), compared to the 7-day average of 7022 cases reported on [2 Aug 2020], a 22% relative decrease.

- Central America
As of [22 Aug 2020], the total confirmed cases (around 266 000) and deaths (7203) have each increased by over 300% in the Central America subregion, compared to the totals (61 058 cases and 1580 deaths) reported in the last PAHO/WHO COVID-19 Epidemiological Update on [23 Jun 2020]. Of the almost 205 000 new cases reported in the last 2 months, the majority were reported by Panama (29%), Guatemala (27%), and Honduras (20%). The same 3 countries also made up the majority (83%) of new deaths reported in the subregion, with Guatemala accounting for the highest proportion (36%), followed by Panama (24%) and Honduras (23%). Belize and Costa Rica experienced the highest relative increases in cases compared to the total number of cases reported as of the last PAHO/WHO COVID19 Epidemiological Update on [23 Jun 2020]: a 29-fold increase in Belize (626 new cases) and a nearly 15-fold increase in Costa Rica (about 30 000 new cases). Costa Rica also experienced a 28-fold increase in deaths (328 new deaths) compared to the total number of deaths reported as of [23 Jun 2020].

Notification of daily COVID-19 cases began increasing in EW 13 [22-28 Mar 2020] and reached a peak in EW 30 ([19-25 Jul 2020]), when 29 795 new cases were reported, primarily from Guatemala, Panama, and Honduras (see Figure 4: Distribution of COVID-19 cases by epidemiological week (EW) of notification. Central America subregion. EW 10-EW 34 2020 [1 Mar-22 Aug 2020]). After a 15% decrease in cases during EW 31 [26 Jul-1 Aug 2020], the next substantial difference in the weekly notification of cases occurred between EW 33 and EW 34 [9-22 Aug 2020], when an 8% decrease was observed (see Figure 4).

In the Central America subregion, Panama has reported the highest cumulative incidence of COVID-19 cases (1913 cases per 100 000 population), followed by Costa Rica (571100 000) and Honduras (515/100 000). The highest rates of cumulative deaths per capita were reported by Panama (41 deaths per 100 000 population), Honduras (16/100 000), and Guatemala (14/100 000). To date, all 7 countries in the Central America subregion have reported community transmission per the WHO classification for COVID-19 transmission category. Belize was the last country in the subregion to join that classification rank, when they declared community transmission on [20 Aug 2020] with 553 confirmed cases including 5 deaths.

- Caribbean and Atlantic Ocean Islands
The Caribbean and Atlantic Ocean Islands subregion reported more than 100 000 new cases, including 1384 deaths, since the last PAHO/WHO COVID-19 Epidemiological Update [23 Jun 2020], a 230% and 123% increase in cases and deaths, respectively. 80% of new cases reported in the last 2 months were from the Dominican Republic (59%) and Puerto Rico (21%). The Dominican Republic reported 64% of the new deaths, followed by Puerto Rico (17%) and Haiti (8%). In addition to the Dominican Republic, Puerto Rico, French Guiana, and Haiti, the countries and territories of Aruba, Sint Maarten, Suriname, Trinidad and Tobago, and the US Virgin Islands now also have community transmission.

In this subregion, the notification of daily COVID-19 cases began increasing in EW 12 of 2020 [15-21 Mar 2020] and reached a high of 15 636 new cases reported in EW 31 [26 Jul 2020-1 Aug 2020], primarily from the Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico (see Figure 5: Distribution of COVID-19 cases by epidemiological week (EW) of notification. Caribbean and Atlantic Ocean Islands subregion. EW 10-EW 34 [1 Mar-22 Aug 2020]).

The weekly number of new cases has been fluctuating since EW 31 [26 Jul-1 Aug 2020], with a 15% decrease in EW 32 [2-8 Aug 2020], a 10% increase in EW 33 [9-15 Aug 2020], followed by a 10% decrease in EW 34 [16-22 Aug 2020], relative to the previous weeks (see Figure 5). Countries and territories such as Aruba, the Bahamas, Sint Maarten, Trinidad and Tobago, and Turks and Caicos generally began reporting an increase in the daily number of cases since the last report, with an acceleration in cases reported in the last 2 weeks; all of which relaxed their social distancing and public health measures in July [2020], including the re-opening of airports.

- South America
Following North America, South America remains the subregion with the highest number of confirmed cases and deaths reported to date. As of [22 Aug 2020], the 10 countries in the subregion have reported a combined total of more than 5.6 million cases, including close to 186 000 deaths, nearly 3 times as many cases and more than twice the number of deaths as reported on 23 June 2020 (about 1 780 000 cases, including about 71 500 deaths). All of the countries have reported community transmission except for Uruguay (clusters of cases).

The shape of the epidemic curve in South America (see Figure 6: Distribution of COVID-19 cases by epidemiological week (EW) of notification. South America subregion. EW 10-EW 34 [1 Mar-22 Aug 2020].) is largely attributed to the situation in Brazil, which has the 2nd highest number of cumulative cases and deaths reported to date at both the global and regional levels. Of the 3.8 million new cases reported in the last 2 months, Brazil accounts for the highest proportion of cases (64%), followed by Colombia (12%), Peru (8%), and Argentina (7%). Similarly, of the 106 000 new deaths, the highest proportions were reported by Brazil (55%), Peru (17%), and Colombia (13%).

In South America, the weekly notification of COVID-19 cases began increasing in EW 13 of 2020 ([22-28 Mar 2020]) and reached a high of more than 530 000 new cases reported in EW 33 [9-15 Aug 2020], primarily from Brazil, Colombia, and Peru (see Figure 6). A 10% decrease in cases was observed in EW 34 [16-22 Aug 2020].

Comorbidities and age as risk factors for COVID-19
--------------------------------------------------
Comorbidities and outcomes among COVID-19 reported cases in Latin America and the Caribbean
As part of the incident management system established to respond to the COVID-19 pandemic, countries of the Region of the Americas have reported individual-level data for COVID-19 probable and confirmed cases, including demographic, clinical, and epidemiological characteristics, as well as information on potential risk factors for both SARS-CoV-2 infection and complications following infection [details available at source URL above -- downloaded document]

COVID-19 among indigenous populations
-------------------------------------
From the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic in the Region of the Americas and until 22 Aug 2020, 93 622 confirmed cases, including 1893 deaths (2.0%), were reported among indigenous peoples or communities in 11 countries for which information was available in the Americas.

Comparing the current data with the data published in the PAHO/WHO Epidemiological Update on [5 Aug 2020], 14 the highest relative increase in the number of cases has been observed among the indigenous peoples of Colombia, followed by Ecuador and Brazil. With regards to the number of deaths, the highest relative increase has been observed in Ecuador, followed by Colombia (see Table 1: Number of confirmed cases and deaths of COVID-19 among indigenous peoples in the Region of the Americas. 1 Jan to 21 Aug 2020.)

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Marianne Hopp

[The region of the Americas has been the hardest hit of the WHO regions with the USA, Brazil, Mexico, Chile, Argentina, and Peru among the dominant countries globally. The report above highlights the toll taken on the smaller populated countries and territories in the region. The increase in the Caribbean countries has been attributed to the opening up of the countries to tourism again and, as seen in other regions, opening up of restrictions has led to vacationers who are behaving as though the virus is no longer a threat. - Mod.MPP]

